%==== 4b. Data findings =======================================================%

\begin{frame}{Index Construction Results: Temporary CSI -- Error Costs}
\scriptsize
\begin{alertblock}{Where the winning temporary strategies benefit}
\scriptsize
The filtered portfolios give up return through false positives, but offset this mainly through retained true-negative exposure. Small Cap has the largest return improvement and also the largest false-positive drag.
\end{alertblock}

\vspace{0.05em}
\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{2.4pt}
\begin{tabular}{L{1.8cm}L{1.65cm}R{0.9cm}R{0.9cm}R{0.9cm}R{0.9cm}R{0.75cm}}
\toprule
Universe & Best rule & FP cost & FN cost & TP gain & TN gain & Net \\
\midrule
Total Market & FPR3 / 5yr & -0.970 & -0.003 & +0.064 & +1.028 & +0.119 \\
Large Cap & FPR1 / 1yr & -0.018 & +0.000 & +0.000 & -0.002 & -0.020 \\
Mid Cap & Youden / 1yr & -3.552 & +0.000 & -0.004 & +3.586 & +0.030 \\
Small Cap & Youden / 3yr & -7.648 & -0.034 & +0.463 & +8.591 & +1.372 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\vspace{0.2em}
\scriptsize
Interpretation: The true-positive protection is positive but small. The key tradeoff is whether retained non-CSI exposure compensates for false-positive opportunity costs.
\remarkfoot{Annualized pp terms. TN gain is the geometric-return balancing retained-exposure term, so FP+FN+TP+TN equals Net.}
\end{frame}

%==== 4b. Data findings =======================================================%

