%==== 4b. Data findings =======================================================%

\begin{frame}{Index Construction Results: Permanent CSI - Error Costs}
\scriptsize
\begin{alertblock}{Where the winning permanent strategies benefit}
\scriptsize
Permanent CSI improves Total, Large, and Mid Cap primarily through true-negative retained exposure after absorbing removals. Small Cap remains weak because false-positive costs absorb the benefit.
\end{alertblock}

\vspace{0.05em}
\begin{table}[ht]
\centering
\setlength{\tabcolsep}{2.4pt}
\begin{tabular}{L{1.8cm}L{1.65cm}R{0.9cm}R{0.9cm}R{0.9cm}R{0.9cm}R{0.75cm}}
\toprule
Universe & Best rule & FP cost & FN cost & TP gain & TN gain & Net \\
\midrule
Total Market & FPR3 / perm. & -1.261 & -0.001 & +0.022 & +1.712 & +0.472 \\
Large Cap & FPR3 / perm. & -0.849 & +0.000 & +0.000 & +1.194 & +0.345 \\
Mid Cap & FPR1 / perm. & -0.167 & +0.000 & +0.000 & +0.593 & +0.426 \\
Small Cap & FPR3 / perm. & -3.109 & -0.017 & +0.076 & +3.008 & -0.042 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\vspace{0.2em}
\scriptsize
Read: the strongest permanent-CSI case is not direct true-positive protection; it is disciplined removal that preserves exposure to retained non-CSI firms while avoiding enough weak names.
\remarkfoot{Annualized pp terms. TN gain is the geometric-return balancing retained-exposure term, so FP+FN+TP+TN equals Net.}
\end{frame}

\section{Next Steps}
\begin{frame}{Next steps before the final presentation}
\small

\begin{alertblock}{Four key areas}
\scriptsize
The proposal lays the methodological and empirical foundation. Remaining work splits into data validation, model interpretability, an optional modeling extension, and an index-construction extension - each connected to a section already in the proposal.
\end{alertblock}

\vspace{0.5em}

\begin{columns}[t]
